sport_group <- subset(PrisonStress, PrisonStress$Group == "Sport")
control_group <- subset(PrisonStress, PrisonStress$Group == "Control")

The above two populations are matched pair We need to figure out whether the training helped the prisoners in terms of the stress levels. For that we can check the mean difference between the two provided groups. We can perform various tests out of which we going to perform the strong test which is t test. For the t-test, we need the data to be normal and equal variance Lets test them for both pssbefore as well as pssafter of difference between them

difference_data = sport_group$PSSafter - sport_group$PSSbefore
#pssbefore
par(mfrow=c(1,2))
hist(difference_data, main = "", xlab ="", 
     col = "lightgoldenrod4", border = "black")
boxplot(difference_data, main = NA, xlab = "", col = "lightgoldenrod4")

From the above chart we can observe that the data was normal. Lets statistically prove them by using the skewness and shapiro-wilk test since the data is discrete.

library(e1071)

cat("difference_data \n")
## difference_data
skewness(difference_data)
## [1] -0.4023306
cat("difference_data shapiro-wilktest\n")
## difference_data shapiro-wilktest
shapiro.test(difference_data)
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  difference_data
## W = 0.95267, p-value = 0.5674

From the shapiro-wilk test it is proven that the data posses normality as the p-values for both the samples are greater than 0.05. Now, we need to verify the variance of both the samples

var.test(sport_group$PSSbefore, sport_group$PSSafter) 
## 
##  F test to compare two variances
## 
## data:  sport_group$PSSbefore and sport_group$PSSafter
## F = 1.175, num df = 14, denom df = 14, p-value = 0.767
## alternative hypothesis: true ratio of variances is not equal to 1
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.394499 3.499989
## sample estimates:
## ratio of variances 
##            1.17505

The data provides insufficient evidence to reject \(H_0\), and conclude equal population variances. As both the normality and equal variance conditions satisfies we can perform t-test. Where following is the null hypothesis and respective alternative hypothesis.

\(H_{0}: \mu_{1} =\mu_{2}\) versus \(H_{1}: \mu_{1} \ne \mu_{2}\).

t.test(sport_group$PSSbefore, sport_group$PSSafter, paired = TRUE)
## 
##  Paired t-test
## 
## data:  sport_group$PSSbefore and sport_group$PSSafter
## t = 2.6842, df = 14, p-value = 0.0178
## alternative hypothesis: true mean difference is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.7904329 7.0762338
## sample estimates:
## mean difference 
##        3.933333

The mean sample difference is \(\overline{d} = 3.933333\).

The paired \(t\)-statistic for testing \(H_{0}: \mu_{1} =\mu_{2}\) versus \(H_{1}: \mu_{1} \ne \mu_{2}\). is \(2.6842\) with \(n-1 = 13\) d.f. The \(p\)-value is \(0.0178\).

The \(95\%\) C.I. for \(\mu_d\) is \((0.7904329 7.0762338)\), which contains the value \(0\) hypothesized under \(H_0\). We conclude that the data does provide evidence to reject \(H_0\) at level of significance \(\alpha =0.05\), so the there is a considerable effect of the sport training on the prisoners.

Effect size tells us how meaningful the relationship between variables or the difference between groups is, i.e., it indicates the practical significance of a research outcome. A large effect size means that a research finding has practical significance, whereas the medium effect size indicates the noticeable significant while a small effect size indicates limited practical applications.

We can obtain the effect size using Cohens D. As expected, the effect size of the difference between PSSbefore and PSSafter is medium.

library(effsize)
# Cohen's d for paired $t$ procedure
cohen.d(sport_group$PSSbefore, sport_group$PSSafter, paired = TRUE)
## 
## Cohen's d
## 
## d estimate: 0.5440526 (medium)
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##      lower      upper 
## 0.09920296 0.98890233

The paired \(t\)-procedure is valid for the data and is more powerful.

  1. Since the normality assumption holds for both populations, we use the \(F\)-test for checking \(H_{0}: \sigma_{1}^{2}=\sigma_{2}^{2}\) versus \(H_1: \sigma^2_1 \neq \sigma^2_2\). The test statistic is the ratio of the sample variances:

\[ F=S_{1}^{2}/S_{2}^{2} \sim F_{n_{1}-1, n_{2}-1}. \]

# F-test for equal variance
var.test(control_group$PSSafter, sport_group$PSSafter)
## 
##  F test to compare two variances
## 
## data:  control_group$PSSafter and sport_group$PSSafter
## F = 1.0609, num df = 10, denom df = 14, p-value = 0.8951
## alternative hypothesis: true ratio of variances is not equal to 1
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.3371169 3.7664880
## sample estimates:
## ratio of variances 
##            1.06086

From the above p-value we fail to reject the null hypothesis and can confirm that the two populations variances are equal.

1.d. As both normal and the equal variance holds we can continue with the pooled t-test

t.test(PSSafter ~ Group, data=PSS, alternative = c("greater"),var.equal = TRUE)
## 
##  Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  PSSafter by Group
## t = 1.3424, df = 24, p-value = 0.09601
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means between group Control and group Sport is greater than 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -1.023091       Inf
## sample estimates:
## mean in group Control   mean in group Sport 
##              23.72727              20.00000

From the above pooled t-test the p value is greater than the \(\alpha\) value of 0.05 and so we accept the null hypothesis and conclude that there is no considerable difference between the two populations(control and sport) at the time of exit.

As the normality asumptions was not satisfied we can go with the Paired Fishers sign procedure

library("BSDA")

For the effect size to calculate we can apply Wilcoxon Signed-Rank Effect Size for the fishers sign test as it is non-parametric

data <- diff_loblolly

# Calculate the absolute differences
differences <- diff(data)
# Rank the absolute differences (ignore the sign)
ranked_differences <- rank(abs(differences))
# Calculate the sum of ranks for positive differences
positive_sum_ranks <- sum(ranked_differences[differences > 0])
# Calculate the sum of ranks for negative differences
negative_sum_ranks <- sum(ranked_differences[differences < 0])
# Determine the smaller of the two sums of ranks
smaller_sum_ranks <- min(positive_sum_ranks, negative_sum_ranks)
# Calculate the effect size (r)
N <- length(data) - 1  # Number of pairs
effect_size_r <- smaller_sum_ranks / N
# Print the effect size (r)
print(effect_size_r)
## [1] 3.230769

From the above Fishers sign result, the p-value is extremely small and so we reject null hypothesis of mean differences of two populations are equal and so we conclude that the mean difference of both populations are not equal and alongside effect size also indicates that there is a noticeable practical significance.

  1. For the given two independent samples if the conclusion was drawn from two-sample pooled t-test that means that the following assumptions were already satisfied such as normality and the equal variances whereas the Wilcoxons rank-sum test is specifically suitable for the case where the data not even symmetry. Moreover, the two-sample pooled t-test is the most powerful test as it provides the precise information about the mean differences on comparison with the Wilcoxons rank-sum test whereas it is the least powerful test.

I would recommend, two-sample pooled t-test when the assumptions such as the normality and the equal variances of the data was met as as it is more statistically powerful if at all the assumptions were not satisfied including the symmetry we can choose Wilcoxons rank-sum test.

  1. P-value controversy and its understanding is one of the majorly debated topics in the statistical field because of the nuanced interpretation of the p-values which sometimes even mislead the data to the wrong dirrection. It is true that the p-values are helpful for the taking decisions on the data however it should not be only considered as primary concluder as practical significance also shows considerable effect on the data. One can take effect sizes, confidence intervals, domain knowledge in conjunction with the p-values to take a concrete decision on the data. Moreover, overlying solely on the p-values could lead to p-hacking or overly definitive conclusions.

As an emerging data scientist, I would like to recognize the importance of a more comprehensive interpretation of the data such as the effect size, context, practical significance along side the p-values to make a resonable decisions and analysis on the data. Most importantly, updating myself on the latest methods, practices and embracing a holistic approach to the data analysis where p-values are just one tool in the toolbox.
